"Planton S.","Global warming and El Nino: A review of the current knowledge [Rechauffement global et El Nino: Une revue des connaissances actuelles]",1999,"Medecine et Maladies Infectieuses","29","5",,"267","276",,,10.1016/S0399-077X(99)80056-0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033133389&partnerID=40&md5=8b2c3f92e7194647e3781ad254eeefd7","Météo France, Ctr. Natl. de Rech. Meteorologiques, 42, avenue G. Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse, France","Planton, S., Météo France, Ctr. Natl. de Rech. Meteorologiques, 42, avenue G. Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse, France","The observations of temperature from meteorological networks, as independent observations or indicators (paleoclimatic, snow cover, sea-ice and glaciers extensions, sea level), tend towards a surface global warming, which has been more intense during the last decades. Several studies converge on the attribution of part of the most recent warming to human activities. The El Nino event (and its companion La Nina) of climate variability, induces climate anomalies which can be distributed all over the globe. The forecasting of these events, several season in advance, became foreseeable a few years ago. These forecasts, as climate change predictions, can be used as input to impact studies on the occurrence and extension of infectious diseases. It appears important that the corresponding methodologies account for the uncertainties of the climatic forecasts and predictions.","Climatology; Infectious diseases","environmental factor; global climate; greenhouse effect; infection; infection risk; prediction; review; seasonal variation",,,,,,"McMichael, A., Ando, M., Carcavallo, R., Epstein, P., Haines, A., Jendritsky, G., Human population health (1995) Climate Change 1995, Impacts, Adaptations and Mitigation of Climate Change: Scientific-technical Analysis, pp. 561-584. , Watson R, Zinyowera M, Moss H, Dokken D. eds. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Colwell, R., Global climate and infectious disease: The cholera paradigm (1996) Science, 274, pp. 2025-2031; Houghton, J., Meira Filho, L., Callander, B., Harris, N., Kattenberg, A., Maskell, K., (1995) Climate Change: The Science of Climate Change, , Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Robock, A., Jianping, M., The volcanic signal in surface temperature observations (1995) J Climate, 8, pp. 1086-1102; Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Sato, M., Global surface air temperature in 1995: Return to pre-Pinatubo level (1995) Geophys Res Let, 23, pp. 1665-1668; Jones, P., Groisman, P., Coughan, M., Plummer, N., Wang, W., Karl, T., Assessment of urbanization effects in time series of surface air temperature over land (1990) Nature, 347, pp. 169-172; Moberg, A., Alexandersson, H., Homogenization of swedish temperature data. Part II: Homogenized gridded air temperature compared with a subset of global gridded air temperature since 1861 (1997) Int J Climatol, 17, pp. 35-54; Tett, S., Mitchell, J., Parker, D., Allen, M., Human influence on the atmospheric vertical temperature structure: Detection and observations (1996) Science, 274, pp. 1170-1173; Luers, J., Eskridge, R., Use of radiosonde temperature data in climate studies (1998) J Climate, 11, pp. 1002-1019; Wentz, F., Schabel, F., Effects of orbital decay on satellite-derived lower-troposperic temperature trends (1998) Nature, 394, pp. 661-664; Oerlemans, J., Quantifying global warming from the retreat of glaciers (1994) Science, 264, pp. 243-245; Hodge, A., Trabant, D., Krimmel, M., Heinrichs, T., March, R., Josberger, E., Climate variations and changes in mass of three glaciers in Western North America (1998) J Climate, 11, pp. 2161-2179; Robinson, D., Dewey, K., Heim, R., Global snow cover monitoring: An update (1993) Bull Am Meteor Soc, 74, pp. 1689-1696; Cavalieri, D., Gloersen, P., Parkinson, C., Comiso, J., Zwally, H., Observed hemispheric assymmetry in global sea ice changes (1997) Science, 278, pp. 1104-1106; Gornitz, V., Rozenweig, S., Is sea level rising or falling (1997) Natur